An Argia sedula is a species of damselfly found in North America.
It has a slender body and narrow wings that fold close to the body when at rest.
The males have a blue-green coloration on the thorax and abdomen, while the females have a more subdued greenish-brown coloration.
The eyes are large and protruding, and are generally a bright green in color.
Argia sedula are primarily found near freshwater habitats such as streams and rivers.
They are often seen perched on vegetation near the water's edge, or darting about in flight.
These damselflies play an important role in their ecosystem as both predators and prey for a variety of other animals.
